<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n47141a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n47" href="#n47141a">N47 (VI.B.40)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n47all.htm#n47141a"> 141(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ab</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">4. The <i>ab</i> <font color="green">[image]</font>, or heart, was closely associated with the soul, and it was held to be the source both of the animal life and of good and evil in man. The preservation of the heart of a man was held to be of the greatest importance, and in the Judgement it is the one member of the body which is singled out for special examination. <font color="green">[It]</font> typified everything which the word &ldquo;conscience&rdquo; signifies to us. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD3"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a>, 2nd Ed (1909) lx [The constituent parts of man physically, mentally, and spiritually]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
